17 barriers; and
18 WHEREAS, in 2022, Valerie was honored with The Leukemia & Lymphoma Society (LLS)
19 Advocacy Champion of the Year award, a testament to her selfless dedication to advancing
20 the LLS mission and her commitment to policy change that benefits the millions of
21 Americans without access to Medicaid; and
22 WHEREAS, through her relentless advocacy, including engaging in virtual meetings with
23 lawmakers, her powerful story featured in The Leukemia & Lymphoma's annual report,
24 having her story featured in The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, and her pivotal role in creating
25 a compelling Medicaid Coverage Gap video, Valerie has amplified the voices of those in
26 need, becoming a driving force in advancing the legislative agenda for improved and
27 equitable access to care; and
28 WHEREAS, Valerie has also been an active member of LLS's Team in Training program,
29 raising nearly $5,000 through a personal fundraiser and completing a 35-mile ride in
30 America's Most Beautiful Bike Ride in Lake Tahoe, further supporting LLS's efforts to fund
31 research and provide hope to patients; and
32 WHEREAS, Valerie continues to advocate for safer, more accessible treatments for all
33 cancer patients and remains unwavering in her commitment to closing the healthcare
34 coverage gap, ensuring that every Georgian has access to the life-saving care they need and
35 deserve; and
36 WHEREAS, Valerie's unwavering courage and determination are an inspiration to all, and
37 her work as The Leukemia & Lymphoma Society's Advocacy Leader for Georgia represents
